{"title_page": "Shane Lemieux", "text_new": "{{short description|American football Guard}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Shane Lemieux\n|school=Oregon Ducks\n|currentnumber=68\n|currentposition=[[Guard (gridiron football)|Guard]]\n|class={{redshirt}} Senior\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2017 Las Vegas Bowl]]\n*[[2018 Redbox Bowl]]\n*[[2020 Rose Bowl]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1997|5|12}}\n|birth_place=\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=4\n|weight=316\n|highlights=\n* 2\u00d7 Second-team All-[[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] ([[2018 All-Pac-12 Conference football team|2018]], [[2019 Pac-12 Conference football season#awards|2019]])\n|highschool=[[West Valley High School (Yakima, Washington)|West Valley]] <br>([[Yakima, Washington]])<br />\n|pastschools= [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]] (2015\u20132019)\n|espn=3915142\n}}\n'''Shane Lemieux''' is an American football [[Guard (gridiron football)|guard]] who played college football at [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]].\n\n==College career==\nAfter playing at [[West Valley High School (Yakima, Washington)|West Valley High School]] as a tight end and offensive lineman,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Brugler |first1=Dane |title=The Athletic's 2020 NFL Draft Guide |date=April 7, 2020 |publisher=The Athletic |page=106 |url=https://cdn.theathletic.com/app/uploads/2020/04/21144256/2020-NFL-DRAFT-FINAL-2.pdf |url-access=subscription |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Lemieux committed to [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]] on May 3, 2014, choosing the Ducks over [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]], [[Boise State Broncos football|Boise State]] and others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shane Lemieux, West Valley, Offensive Guard |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Shane-Lemieux-40610/high-school-66990/ |website=247Sports |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhile Lemieux redshirted his freshman season, he did not miss a start between 2016 and 2019, starting 52 games over those four seasons.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL Draft & Combine Profile - Shane Lemieux |url=https://www.nfl.com/prospects/shane-lemieux?id=32194c45-4d28-9885-7e91-71edd7d31c9a |website=NFL.com |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter his junior season, Lemieux and a group of teammates (including quarterback [[Justin Herbert]]) considered leaving for the NFL Draft, but collectively decided to stay.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Spruill |first1=Scott |title=West Valley's Shane Lemieux takes run of 51 consecutive starts into Rose Bowl |url=https://www.yakimaherald.com/sports/college_sports/west-valley-s-shane-lemieux-takes-run-of-consecutive-starts/article_194e4436-511d-513b-a505-6fba1d547360.html |website=Yakima Herald |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=December 26, 2019}}</ref> Lemieux had also sought out an evaluation from the NFL's College Advisory Board and was advised to return to school.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crepa |first1=James |title=Oregon left guard Shane Lemieux will return in 2019 |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/ducks/2018/12/oregon-left-guard-shane-lemieux-will-return-in-2019.html |website=The Oregonian |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=December 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter his senior season, Lemieux was named a second-team All-American by both the Associated Press and Sporting News,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crepa |first1=James |title=Shane Lemieux wants NFL teams to see toughness, durability that allowed him to start 52 games for Oregon Ducks |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/ducks/2020/02/shane-lemieux-wants-nfl-teams-to-see-toughness-durability-that-allowed-him-to-start-52-games-for-oregon-ducks.html |website=The Oregonian |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> and was named first-team all-Pac-12.<ref>{{cite web |title=West Valley's Lemieux second-team AP All-American |url=https://www.yakimaherald.com/news/news_watch/west-valley-s-lemieux-second-team-ap-all-american/article_351be07d-b6ce-59db-bf6e-47bac06708d1.html |website=Yakima Herald |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://goducks.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=8488 Oregon Ducks bio]\n*{{twitter|ShaneLemieux}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lemieux, Shane}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:American football guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Yakima, Washington]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Oregon Ducks football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|American football Guard}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Shane Lemieux\n|school=Oregon Ducks\n|currentnumber=68\n|currentposition=[[Guard (gridiron football)|Guard]]\n|class={{redshirt}} Senior\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2017 Las Vegas Bowl]]\n*[[2018 Redbox Bowl]]\n*[[2020 Rose Bowl]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1997|5|12}}\n|birth_place=\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=4\n|weight=316\n|highlights=\n* 2\u00d7 Second-team All-[[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] ([[2018 All-Pac-12 Conference football team|2018]], [[2019 Pac-12 Conference football season#awards|2019]])\n|highschool=[[West Valley High School (Yakima, Washington)|West Valley]] <br>([[Yakima, Washington]])<br />\n|pastschools= [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]] (2015\u20132019)\n|espn=3915142\n}}\n'''Shane Lemieux''' is an American football [[Guard (gridiron football)|guard]] who played college football at [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]].\n\n==College career==\nAfter playing at [[West Valley High School (Yakima, Washington)|West Valley High School]] as a tight end and offensive lineman,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Brugler |first1=Dane |title=The Athletic's 2020 NFL Draft Guide |date=April 7, 2020 |publisher=The Athletic |page=106 |url=https://cdn.theathletic.com/app/uploads/2020/04/21144256/2020-NFL-DRAFT-FINAL-2.pdf |url-access=subscription |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Lemieux committed to [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]] on May 3, 2014, choosing the Ducks over [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]], [[Boise State Broncos football|Boise State]] and others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shane Lemieux, West Valley, Offensive Guard |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Shane-Lemieux-40610/high-school-66990/ |website=247Sports |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhile Lemieux redshirted his freshman season, he did not miss a start between 2016 and 2019, starting 52 games over those four seasons.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL Draft & Combine Profile - Shane Lemieux |url=https://www.nfl.com/prospects/shane-lemieux?id=32194c45-4d28-9885-7e91-71edd7d31c9a |website=NFL.com |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter his junior season, Lemieux and a group of teammates (including quarterback [[Justin Herbert]]) considered leaving for the NFL Draft, but collectively decided to stay.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Spruill |first1=Scott |title=West Valley's Shane Lemieux takes run of 51 consecutive starts into Rose Bowl |url=https://www.yakimaherald.com/sports/college_sports/west-valley-s-shane-lemieux-takes-run-of-consecutive-starts/article_194e4436-511d-513b-a505-6fba1d547360.html |website=Yakima Herald |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=December 26, 2019}}</ref> Lemieux had also sought out an evaluation from the NFL's College Advisory Board and was advised to return to school.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crepa |first1=James |title=Oregon left guard Shane Lemieux will return in 2019 |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/ducks/2018/12/oregon-left-guard-shane-lemieux-will-return-in-2019.html |website=The Oregonian |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=December 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter his senior season, Lemieux was named a second-team All-American by both the Associated Press and Sporting News,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crepa |first1=James |title=Shane Lemieux wants NFL teams to see toughness, durability that allowed him to start 52 games for Oregon Ducks |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/ducks/2020/02/shane-lemieux-wants-nfl-teams-to-see-toughness-durability-that-allowed-him-to-start-52-games-for-oregon-ducks.html |website=The Oregonian |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> and was named first-team all-Pac-12.<ref>{{cite web |title=West Valley's Lemieux second-team AP All-American |url=https://www.yakimaherald.com/news/news_watch/west-valley-s-lemieux-second-team-ap-all-american/article_351be07d-b6ce-59db-bf6e-47bac06708d1.html |website=Yakima Herald |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://goducks.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=8488 Oregon Ducks bio]\n*{{twitter|ShaneLemieux}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lemieux, Shane}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:American football guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Yakima, Washington]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Oregon Ducks football players]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, removed orphan tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shane_Lemieux"}
{"title_page": "Dalton Keene", "text_new": "{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Dalton Keene\n|image=\n|image_size= \n|caption=\n|school=Virginia Tech Hokies\n|currentnumber=29\n|currentposition=[[Tight end]]\n|class=Junior\n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=4\n|weight_lb=251\n|highlights=\n|bowlgames=\n|highschool=[[Chatfield High School (Colorado)|Chatfield]]<br>([[Littleton, Colorado]])\n|pastschools=\n*[[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]] (2017\u20132019)\n|espn=4240861\n}}\n\n'''Dalton Keene''' is an [[American football]] [[tight end]]. He played [[college football]] for the [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech Hokies]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nKeene grew up in [[Littleton, Colorado]] and attended Chatfield High School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/04/20/chatfield-dalton-keene-virginia-tech-nfl-draft/|title=Chatfield alum Dalton \"Rambo\" Keene projected as late-round pick out of Virginia Tech|work=[[The Denver Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nKeene started 12 games as a true freshman and caught 10 passes for 167 yards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/broncos/draft/virginia-tech-te-dalton-keene-checks-multiple-denver-broncos-boxes|title=Colorado Native TE Dalton Keene Checks Multiple Boxes for Broncos in Draft|website=Maven}}</ref> He was named honorable mention All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] after recording 28 receptions for 341 yards and three touchdowns in his sophomore season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegram.com/news/20200409/patriots-tight-end-could-become-focal-point-in-draft|title=Patriots: Tight end could become focal point in draft|first=Mark|last=Daniels, @MarkDanielsPJ|website=telegram.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roanoke.com/z-no-digital/in-the-trenches-with-dalton-keene-for-a-behind-the/article_1a5fabbe-c86e-5193-b8d2-fcd59ccf7475.html|title=\u2018In the trenches\u2019 with Dalton Keene for a behind the scenes look at Virginia Tech\u2019s summer routine|work=[[Roanoke Times]]|date=June 15, 2019}}</ref> As a junior Keene caught 21 passes for 240 yards and five touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roanoke.com/sports/college/va_tech/espns-mel-kiper-ranks-dalton-keene-as-one-of-the-top-tight-ends-available-in/article_bdf32bea-6eb5-11ea-b986-1b76cd61cd9f.html|title=ESPN's Mel Kiper ranks Dalton Keene as one of the top tight ends available in 2020 NFL Draft|work=[[Roanoke Times]]}}</ref> Following the end of the season Keene announced that he would forgo his final year of eligibility to enter the 2020 NFL Draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypress.com/sports/college/virginia-tech/vp-sp-hokies-dalton-keene-nfl-draft-20200421-ql6y32f2ora3nocx6vz7a3rm3y-story.html|title=Hokies\u2019 Dalton Keene hopes his versatility leads to his name being called during the NFL draft|work=[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://hokiesports.com/sports/football/roster/dalton-keene/9567 Virginia Tech Hokies bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Keene, Dalton}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Virginia Tech Hokies football players]]\n[[Category:American football tight ends]]\n\n\n{{Tightend-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Dalton Keene\n|image=\n|image_size= \n|caption=\n|school=Virginia Tech Hokies\n|currentnumber=29\n|currentposition=[[Tight end]]\n|class=Junior\n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=4\n|weight_lb=251\n|highlights=\n|bowlgames=\n|highschool=[[Chatfield High School (Colorado)|Chatfield]]<br>([[Littleton, Colorado]])\n|pastschools=\n*[[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]] (2017\u20132019)\n|espn=4240861\n}}\n\n'''Dalton Keene''' is an [[American football]] [[tight end]]. He played [[college football]] for the [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech Hokies]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nKeene grew up in [[Littleton, Colorado]] and attended Chatfield High School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/04/20/chatfield-dalton-keene-virginia-tech-nfl-draft/|title=Chatfield alum Dalton \"Rambo\" Keene projected as late-round pick out of Virginia Tech|work=[[The Denver Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nKeene started 12 games as a true freshman and caught 10 passes for 167 yards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/broncos/draft/virginia-tech-te-dalton-keene-checks-multiple-denver-broncos-boxes|title=Colorado Native TE Dalton Keene Checks Multiple Boxes for Broncos in Draft|website=Maven}}</ref> He was named honorable mention All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] after recording 28 receptions for 341 yards and three touchdowns in his sophomore season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegram.com/news/20200409/patriots-tight-end-could-become-focal-point-in-draft|title=Patriots: Tight end could become focal point in draft|first=Mark|last=Daniels, @MarkDanielsPJ|website=telegram.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roanoke.com/z-no-digital/in-the-trenches-with-dalton-keene-for-a-behind-the/article_1a5fabbe-c86e-5193-b8d2-fcd59ccf7475.html|title=\u2018In the trenches\u2019 with Dalton Keene for a behind the scenes look at Virginia Tech\u2019s summer routine|work=[[Roanoke Times]]|date=June 15, 2019}}</ref> As a junior Keene caught 21 passes for 240 yards and five touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roanoke.com/sports/college/va_tech/espns-mel-kiper-ranks-dalton-keene-as-one-of-the-top-tight-ends-available-in/article_bdf32bea-6eb5-11ea-b986-1b76cd61cd9f.html|title=ESPN's Mel Kiper ranks Dalton Keene as one of the top tight ends available in 2020 NFL Draft|work=[[Roanoke Times]]}}</ref> Following the end of the season Keene announced that he would forgo his final year of eligibility to enter the 2020 NFL Draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypress.com/sports/college/virginia-tech/vp-sp-hokies-dalton-keene-nfl-draft-20200421-ql6y32f2ora3nocx6vz7a3rm3y-story.html|title=Hokies\u2019 Dalton Keene hopes his versatility leads to his name being called during the NFL draft|work=[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://hokiesports.com/sports/football/roster/dalton-keene/9567 Virginia Tech Hokies bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Keene, Dalton}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Virginia Tech Hokies football players]]\n[[Category:American football tight ends]]\n\n\n{{Tightend-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, removed orphan tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dalton_Keene"}
{"title_page": "2019 Virginia Tech Hokies football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year = 2019\n  |team = Virginia Tech Hokies\n  |sport = football\n  |image = Virginia Tech Hokies logo.svg\n  |image_size = 200\n  |conference = Atlantic Coast Conference\n  |division = Coastal Division\n  |short_conf = ACC\n | CoachRank = \n | APRank = \n | CFPRank =\n  |record = 8\u20135\n  |conf_record = 5\u20133\n  |head_coach = [[Justin Fuente]]\n  |hc_year = 4th\n  |off_coach = Brad Cornelsen\n  |off_scheme = \n  |oc_year = 4th\n  |def_coach = [[Bud Foster]]\n  |dc_year = 25th\n  |def_scheme =\n  |stadium = [[Lane Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 66,233)\n  |bowl = [[2019 Belk Bowl|Belk Bowl]]\n  |bowl_result = L 30\u201337 vs. [[2019 Kentucky Wildcats football team|Kentucky]]\n}}\n{{2019 ACC football standings}}\nThe '''2019 Virginia Tech Hokies football team''' represented [[Virginia Tech]] during the [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Hokies were led by fourth-year head coach [[Justin Fuente]] and played their home games at [[Lane Stadium]] in [[Blacksburg, Virginia]]. They competed as members of the Coastal Division of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC).\nIn one of the most devastating loses in recent memory, the Hokies lost to arch rival Virginia for the first time since 2003. The loss cost the Hokies the Coastal Division and a trip to the Orange Bowl.\n\n==Preseason==\n===Preseason media poll===\nIn the preseason ACC media poll, Virginia Tech was predicted to finish in third in the Coastal Division.<ref>{{cite web|title=Clemson Favored to Continue ACC Football Championship Run|url=http://theacc.com/news/2019/7/22/clemson-favored-to-continue-acc-football-championship-run.aspx|website=theACC.com|publisher=Atlantic Coast Conference|date=July 22, 2019|accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"display: inline-table;\"\n|align=\"center\" Colspan=\"3\" |'''Media poll (Coastal Division)'''\n|- align=\"center\"\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Virginia Tech Hokies|Predicted finish|Team|Votes (1st place)}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1 || Virginia || 1003 (82)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2 || Miami (FL) || 992 (55)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 3 || '''Virginia Tech''' || 827 (20)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 4 || Pittsburgh || 691 (8)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 5 || Duke || 566 (6)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 6 || North Carolina || 463 (1)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 7 || Georgia Tech || 302 (1)\n|}\n\n==Schedule==\nIn non-conference play, Virginia Tech played home games against [[2019 Old Dominion Monarchs football team|Old Dominion]] of [[Conference USA]], [[2019 Furman Paladins football team|Furman]] of the [[Southern Conference]], and [[2019 Rhode Island Rams football team|Rhode Island]] of the [[Colonial Athletic Association]], as well as a road game against [[2019 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]], a [[NCAA Division I FBS independent schools|football independent]]. In [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] play, the Hokies will play the other members of the Coastal Division as well as [[2019 Boston College Eagles football team|Boston College]] and [[2019 Wake Forest Demon Deacons football team|Wake Forest]] from the Atlantic Division.\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 2019\n| poll = [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings#AP Poll|AP Poll]] and [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings#CFP Rankings|CFP Rankings]] after November 5 released prior to game\n| timezone = Eastern\n| time = y\n| tv = y\n| attend = y\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = August 31\n| time = 4:00 p.m.\n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[2019 Boston College Eagles football team|Boston College]]\n| stadium = [[Alumni Stadium]]\n| cityst = [[Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts|Chestnut Hill, MA]]\n| gamename = [[Boston College\u2013Virginia Tech football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| tv = [[ACC Network|ACCN]]\n| score = [https://www.espn.com/college-football/game/_/gameId/401112435 28\u2013