{"title_page": "Centrica", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name      =  Centrica plc\n| logo      =  Centrica logo.svg\n| type      = [[Public limited company]]\n| traded_as = {{lse|CNA}}<br />[[FTSE 100 Index|FTSE 100 Component]]\n| foundation        = {{start date and age|1997|02|17}}\n| location          = [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]], England, UK\n| key_people        = {{ubl|{{wd-chairperson}}|{{wd-ceo}}}}\n| industry          =  Utilities\n| products          =\n| revenue           =  {{decrease}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]26.825&nbsp;billion (2019)<ref name=prelims>{{cite web|url=https://www.centrica.com/media/4012/prelims-announcement-2019-final.pdf|title=Preliminary Results 2018 |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_income  = {{decrease}} \u00a30.901&nbsp;billion (2019)<ref name=prelims/>\n| net_income        =  {{decrease}} \u00a3(1.103)&nbsp;billion (2019)<ref name=prelims/>\n| num_employees     =\n| parent            =\n| subsid            =  See below\n| homepage          =  {{URL|http://www.centrica.com/}}\n| footnotes         =\n}}\n\n'''Centrica plc''' is a British [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] energy and services company with its headquarters in [[Windsor, Berkshire]]. Its principal activity is the [[Electricity supply|supply of electricity]] and [[Natural gas|gas]] to businesses and consumers in the United Kingdom, Ireland and North America.\n\nIt is the largest supplier of gas to domestic customers in the United Kingdom, and one of the largest suppliers of electricity, operating under the trading names [[Scottish Gas]] in Scotland and [[British Gas]] in England and Wales. It owns [[Bord Gais Energy|Bord G\u00e1is Energy]] in Ireland. It is also active in the provision of household services including plumbing.\n\nCentrica is listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]], and is a constituent of the [[FTSE 100 Index]].\n{{TOC limit|limit=3}}\n\n==History==\n\n===Historical origins===\nThe company has its historical origin in the [[Gas Light and Coke Company]] which incorporated in 1812. Over the next 137 years, it grew by acquisition of other gas companies to become the primary supplier of gas to [[Greater London]]. In 1949, under the [[Gas Act 1948]] the ownership of the company transferred to a government agency, [[North Thames Gas Board]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/search2?coll_id=1167&inst_id=14 |title=Gas, Light and Coke Company |last= |first= |date= |work=Archives in the M25 area |publisher=AIM25 |accessdate=}}</ref> The various area [[gas board]]s were merged into the national [[British Gas Corporation]] in 1973. The [[Gas Act 1986]] sold the company to private investors as [[British Gas plc]].<ref>{{cite web|title=30 SECOND GUIDE: Tell Sid|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/news/article-2072001/30-SECOND-GUIDE-Tell-Sid.html|date=2012-07-17|accessdate=2012-12-29}}</ref>\n\n===Origin===\nCentrica became a separate, distinct corporation on 17 February 1997, when [[British Gas plc]] split (demerged) to form three separate companies: Centrica plc, [[BG Group plc|BG plc]] and [[National Grid plc|Transco plc]].  Centrica took over gas sales and gas trading, services and retail businesses, together with the gas production operations in the North and South Morecambe gas fields ([[Rampside Gas Terminal]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12078257.Green_light_for_split_British_Gas_divides_with_aim_of_conquering_market/|title=Green light for split British Gas divides with aim of conquering market|date=13 February 1997|newspaper=Herald Scotland|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Centrica's supplier monopoly for gas came to an end. Centrica maintained the British Gas retail brand but is only allowed to use this brand name in the United Kingdom. The electricity market also opened up to competition and, through the British Gas brand, the company started supplying its first domestic electricity customers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theenergyshop.com/HomeEnergy/advice-guides-deregulationHistory#.Vu77iPmLQdU|title=An alternative history of energy deregulation and energy price comparison in the UK|publisher=The energy shop|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===1998 to 2010===\nAt the end of 1998, under CEO Sir Roy Gardner and Finance Director Mark Clare, Centrica attempted to diversify \u2013 firstly by developing the Goldfish credit card,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/1476617.stm |title=Centrica pays \u00a385m for Goldfish data |work=BBC News |date=6 August 2001 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> then in July 1999, by acquiring the [[The Automobile Association|AA]] for \u00a31.1&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/the_company_file/386200.stm |title=Power firm buys AA |work=BBC News |date=5 July 1999 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> In July 2001, Centrica further diversified with the opportunistic purchase of OneTel in the United Kingdom, a residential telecoms operator.<ref>{{cite news|first=Richard |last=Wray |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2001/jul/04/citynews.media |title=Centrica purchase builds up telecoms business |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date= 4 July 2001|accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nSoon afterwards, Centrica acquired the Dyno franchise group (best known for its [[Dyno-Rod]] drains unblocking service).<ref>{{cite web|author=This is Money|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/news/article.html?in_article_id=317904&in_page_id=2 |title=Dyno-Rod in Centrica's sights? |work=Daily Mail |date=16 August 2004 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Centrica also moved into the North American energy supply market, through the acquisition of the Canada-based company [[Direct Energy]] in July 2000, for \u00a3406&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/business/energy-and-utilities/centrica_plans_163_289m_refinancing_move_at_enbridge_1_858131|title=Centrica plans \u00a3289m refinancing move at Enbridge|accessdate=11 February 2012|work=The Scotsman|date=10 December 2002}}</ref> Direct Energy's operations were subsequently considerably expanded through a number of further acquisitions, including of [[Enbridge]] Services for \u00a3437&nbsp;million in January 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/business/energy-and-utilities/centrica_picks_up_an_extra_1_3m_canadian_customers_1_595243|title=Centrica picks up an extra 1.3m Canadian customers|accessdate=11 February 2012|work=The Scotsman|date=29 January 2002}}</ref>\n\nThis strategy of diversification changed in the middle of 2003, possibly under pressure from major city shareholders to deliver better returns and/or possibly anticipating pressure on the core energy supply business. The change of strategy started with the sale of the Goldfish business to Lloyds TSB Bank<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/globalassets/documents/investors/2003/2003aug1_goldfish_acquisition.pdf|title=Rough ruling and Goldfish sale boost Centrica]|accessdate=2015-01-15|publisher=Lloyds PLC}}</ref> (who subsequently sold it to Morgan Stanley Bank International Limited).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/4544520.stm |title=Lloyds TSB sells Goldfish brand |work=BBC News |date=20 December 2005 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThen, in July 2004, Centrica sold the AA to two private equity firms; Luxembourgish [[CVC Capital Partners|CVC]] and British [[Permira]] for \u00a31.75&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3855635.stm |title=Centrica gets bumper price for AA |work=BBC News |date=1 July 2004 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Centrica then acquired [[Dyno-Rod]] in October 2004.<ref name=\"Centrica acquires Dyno-Rod\">{{cite web|title=Centrica acquires Dyno-Rod|url=http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=1090&newsid=444|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119023812/http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=1090&newsid=444|archive-date=19 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Then, in December 2005, Centrica sold their OneTel business to Carphone Warehouse.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/4541148.stm |title=Carphone buys One-tel for \u00a3132m |work=BBC News |date=19 December 2005 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nSince 2005, Centrica has declared a strategy of consolidating within the energy sector, upstream and downstream, including expanding operations overseas. New chairman Roger Carr replaced retiring chairman Sir Michael Perry in 2005, whilst new CEO Sam Laidlaw picked up the reins from retiring CEO Sir Roy Gardner in March 2006.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://businesswriter.wordpress.com/2006/03/14/centricas-new-chief-executive-is-outsider-sam-laidlaw/ |title=Centrica's new Chief Executive is outsider Sam Laidlaw |publisher=Businesswriter.wordpress.com |date=14 March 2006 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006, it was rumoured that the Russian state owned utility company [[Gazprom]] was seeking a takeover of Centrica. This created controversy in the media, while the Department for Trade and Industry stated any deal would be subject to \"intense scrutiny\". [[Tony Blair]] announced in April that he would not block any potential deal.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2937583/Gazprom-free-to-bid-for-Centrica.html Gazprom free to bid for Centrica] ''The Daily Telegraph'', 26 April 2006</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, the company acquired the Caythorpe gas producing field near [[Bridlington]] to use for storage purposes.<ref>{{cite news|date=25 September 2008 |url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/businessnews/Centrica-buys-old-gas-field.4526357.jp |title=Centrica buys old gas field |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> It also agreed to buy 20% of [[British Energy]] from [[EDF Energy|EDF]], financing this with a \u00a32.2&nbsp;billion, 3 for 8 [[rights issue]].<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7701407.stm|publisher=BBC|title=Centrica looks to raise \u00a32.2bn|date=31 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=39&newsid=1845|publisher=Centrica|title=Approval from the OFT of Centrica's acquisition of 20% of British Energy from EDF|date=7 August 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815005829/http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=39&newsid=1845|archivedate=15 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The rights issue offered shares at 160 pence per share and closed on 12 December 2008.<ref>{{cite paper |title=Provisional Allotment Letter |author=Centrica |date=November 2008}}</ref> In August 2009, Centrica took over [[Venture Production]], a North Sea gas producer.<ref>{{Cite news| url =http://www.centrica.co.uk/index.asp?pageid=39&newsid=1856| title =Venture offer \u2013 Centrica achieves 58.7 per cent. level| publisher =Centrica Plc| date =24 August 2009| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090828002117/http://www.centrica.co.uk/index.asp?pageid=39&newsid=1856| archivedate =28 August 2009| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2010 to 2019===\nOn 13 June 2010 Centrica, through Direct Energy, acquired Clockwork Home Services. Combining with the existing energy offer made Centrica the largest provider of heating and cooling, plumbing and electrical services in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.achrnews.com/articles/114114-june-10-2010-clockwork-home-services-sold-to-direct-energy|title=Clockwork Home Services Sold to Direct Energy|date=10 June 2010|website=The News|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> On 17 November 2010, Centrica acquired the assets of heat pump installation company Cool Planet Technologies Ltd. for \u00a30.5 million in cash. This aimed to boost the company's strategy of developing a broad range of low carbon technologies and advice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.energylivenews.com/2010/11/18/british-gas-buys-cool-planet-technologies/|title=British Gas buys Cool Planet Technologies|publisher=Energy Live News|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, Centrica signed a \u00a32&nbsp;billion three-year contract with Qatargas for the purchase of 2.4 million tonnes a year of liquefied natural gas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/centrica-in-2bn-qatar-gas-deal-2223287.html|title=Centrica in \u00a32bn Qatar gas deal|accessdate=11 February 2012|work=The Independent|date=23 February 2011}}</ref> In March 2011, Centrica agreed the sale of the electricity and gas supply business of its Netherlands-based subsidiary [[Oxxio]] to Eneco BV for \u20ac72&nbsp;million (\u00a363&nbsp;million) in cash. The sale completed Centrica's exit from the supply of electricity and gas in Continental Europe, following the earlier disposal of its supply businesses in Belgium and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2011/02/centrica_hopes_to_sell_energy/|title=Centrica hopes to sell energy firm Oxxio this year|date=24 January 2011|publisher=Dutch News|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Centrica agreed to buy $1.6 billion stakes of 8 fields on the Norwegian continental shelf from [[Statoil]] ASA. In a second deal, Centrica agreed to buy 5 billion cubic meters a year gas from the same company from 2015 to 2025 as equal to 5% of gas consumption in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-11-21/centrica-agrees-to-buy-norwegian-gas-stakes-from-statoil-for-1-6-billion.html |title=Centrica Agrees to Buy Norwegian Gas Fields From Statoil for $1.6 Billion |date=22 November 2011 | work=Bloomberg |first1=Eduard |last1=Gismatullin |first2=Kari |last2=Lundgren}}</ref> Centrica's Germany based trading division ''Centrica Energie GmbH'' was closed in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.centrica-energie.de/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070225102739/http://www.centrica-energie.de/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 February 2007 |title=Centrica Energie GmbH |publisher=Centrica-energie.de |accessdate=21 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, it was announced that Centrica would acquire the energy marketing unit of [[Hess Corporation]] for $1.03 billion.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/07/30/us-centrica-idUSBRE96T0MA20130730| title=Hess to sell Energy Marketing unit to UK's Centrica for $1.03 billion | first=Swetha |last=Gopinath |first2=Sarah|last2=Young | agency=Reuters | date=30 July 2013}}</ref> In March 2014, Centrica acquired the retail arm and other assets belonging to Ireland's state owned [[Bord G\u00e1is]] for a fee of around \u20ac1.1 billion.<ref>{{cite news|title= Centrica buys Irish energy supplier as profits sink at home|work= Reuters|date=25 March 2014|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/25/us-centrica-bordgais-idUSBREA2O0F420140325|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Centrica entered into joint venture arrangements with [[Tullow Oil]] to explore for oil in the [[South Lokichar Basin]] in [[Kenya]]. In August 2014, Tullow, the operator, revealed significant oil discoveries had been made in the Etom 1 exploration well and testing block 10BB, which expanded the already proven South Lokichar Basin \"significantly northwards,\" taking in an additional 247 km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=\"TullowKenya\">{{cite news|title=More oil discovery announced by Tullow in Kenya|url=http://www.kenyastar.com/index.php/sid/225199123|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=28 August 2014|publisher=Kenya Star}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Centrica established [[Hive Connected Home|Hive]] as part of its Connected Home offering, building on its Remote Heating Control service provided through its British Gas subsidiary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/hive-2-begins-major-push-by-british-gas-into-smart-home-range-connected-devices-1510864|title=Hive 2 begins major push by British Gas into smart home with range of connected devices|website=International Business Times|date=16 July 2015|accessdate=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, in light of significantly changed circumstances, a fundamental strategic review was launched. This focused on outlook and sources of growth; portfolio mix and capital intensity; operating capability and efficiency; and Group financial framework. The review was a thorough and rigorous analysis of the Group's prospects, led by Centrica's senior management. It concluded that Centrica's strength lay in being a customer-facing business and that all activities and priorities would focus on meeting customers' changing needs. The shape of the Group would be reworked to reflect this, including a Group-wide efficiency programme that would reduce employee numbers by around 6,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/jul/30/british-gas-owner-centrica-cuts-thousands-of-jobs-group-shakeup|title=British Gas owner Centrica cuts thousands of jobs|date=30 July 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlso in February 2015, under its British Gas brand, Centrica completed the acquisition of AlertMe, a connected home company based in the United Kingdom that provided innovative energy management products and services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/16c90ea4-b38d-11e4-a45f-00144feab7de|title=British Gas buys 'smart home' tech company AlertMe|newspaper=Financial Times|date=13 February 2019|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> In November 2015, Direct Energy also acquired Panoramic Power, a provider of device level energy management technology, for $60 million (\u00a339 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/read/direct-energy-buys-panoramic-power-for-60m|title=Direct Energy Buys Panoramic Power for $60M|date=16 November 2015|publisher=Green Tech Media|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Centrica acquired Neas Energy A/S (Neas), one of Europe's providers of energy management and revenue optimisation services for decentralised third-party owned assets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/neas-energy-ma-centrica/centrica-buys-denmark-energy-management-firm-neas-for-170-mln-stg-idUKFWN17O043|title=Centrica buys Denmark energy management firm Neas for 170 mln stg|date=21 April 2016|work=Reuters|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> It also acquired ENER-G Cogen International Limited (\"ENER-G Cogen\"), an established supplier and operator of combined heat and power (CHP) systems and REstore NV, Europe's demand response aggregator.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/read/centrica-buys-ener-g-cogen-for-212-million|title=Centrica Buys ENER-G Cogen for $212 Million|date=23 May 2016|publisher=Green Tech Media|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, it was announced that the CQ Energy Canada Partnership, the Canadian E&P joint venture in which Centrica plc owned a 60% interest, was to be sold to a consortium comprising MIE Holdings Corporation, The Can-China Global Resource Fund and Mercuria for a purchase price of C$722 million (\u00a3413 million) in cash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.energylivenews.com/2017/06/12/centrica-sells-240m-stake-in-canadian-oil-and-gas-firm/|title=Centrica sells \u00a3240m stake in Canadian oil and gas firm|publisher=Energy Live News|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 2017, the company agreed to sell its operational Langage and South Humber Bank combined cycle gas turbine power stations, with a combined capacity of 2.3GW, to EP UK Investments Ltd for \u00a3318million in cash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eppowereurope.cz/en/tiskove-zpravy/eph-buy-langage-south-humber-bank-gas-fired-power-stations-centrica/|title=EPH to buy Langage and South Humber Bank gas-fired power stations from Centrica|date=21 June 2017|publisher=EP Power Europe|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 2017 Centrica launched Spirit Energy as a joint venture with German energy and infrastructure firm Stadtwerke M\u00fcnchen (SWM).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/energyterminal/natural-gas/centrica-launches-spirit-energy-ep-joint-venture/15914|title=Centrica launches Spirit Energy E&P joint venture|publisher=AA Energy|date=11 December 2017|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, the Competition & Markets Authority agreed to grant Centrica plc and Centrica Storage Limited's (CSL's) request to be released from the [[Rough (facility)|Rough]] Undertakings. CSL decided that it could no longer operate Rough as a storage facility as the facility was no longer capable of safe injection operations due to the age and condition of the asset, and that due to the economics of seasonal storage and the cost of refurbishing or rebuilding the facility, neither pathway would be economic.<ref name=rough>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/cma-cases/rough-gas-storage-facility-review-of-undertakings|title=Rough gas storage facility: review of undertakings|date=17 October 2017|publisher=Competition and Markets Authority|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Since 2020===\nIn 2020, following the onset of the 2020 [[coronavirus pandemic]], offices and factories shut and energy use decreased sharply, and the financial problems caused by the pandemic among Centrica's customers will inevitably lead to bad debts. Analysts dropped their estimate of Centrica's earnings for 2020, 2021 and 2022 by 30%. Centrica paused its search for a buyer for its 69% stake in Spirit Energy. The share price in April reached a record low value of \u00a30.30, valuing the company at less than half of its net debt of nearly \u00a34b.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/nils-pratley-on-finance/2020/apr/22/british-gas-owner-needs-more-than-cost-cutting-and-energy-prices-prayer |title=British Gas owner needs more than cost-cutting and energy prices prayer |newspaper=The Guardian |author= |date= 22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n===Organisation===\nCentrica's operations are principally focused on the supply of electricity and gas to businesses and consumers in the United Kingdom and North America. They are organised as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centrica.com/about-us/what-we-do/centrica-business|title=Centrica Business|publisher=Centrica|accessdate=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n* Businesses in the United Kingdom, including [[British Gas]] which supplies gas, electricity and services to residential and business customers\n* Distributed Energy & Power which supports large energy users\n* North America Business including [[Direct Energy]] which supplies gas, electricity and services to residential and business customers\n* Energy Marketing & Trading which provides risk management services\n* Central Power Generation, which has a 20% interest in 8 power stations\n\n=== Shareholdings ===\nIn May 2009, Centrica purchased a 20% stake in nuclear power generator [[British Energy]] from [[EDF Energy]]. The company now produces 14.3% of its electricity from nuclear plants (the second highest rate in the United Kingdom), helping it to achieve the lowest carbon emissions of the major providers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electricity-guide.org.uk/fuel-mix.html |title=Fuel Mix Information |publisher=Electricity-guide.org.uk |date= |accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref> Centrica has also acquired an option to purchase a 20% stake in EDF's subsidiary, [[NNB Generation Company]] (NNB GenCo).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=39&newsid=1783 |title=Centrica to invest in EDF nuclear business in the UK |publisher=Centrica.com |date=31 December 2013 |accessdate=21 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125074949/http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=39 |archivedate=25 November 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Centrica launched a new company as a joint venture with German energy and infrastructure firm [[Stadtwerke M\u00fcnchen]] (SWM). Spirit Energy, an exploration and production (E&P) company, is the result of a combination of Centrica's E&P business and [[Bayerngas Norge]] AS, which was formerly majority-owned by SWM. Centrica plc owns 69% of Spirit Energy, with Bayerngas Norge's former shareholders, led by SWM and Bayerngas GmbH, owning 31%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cityam.com/277278/british-gas-owner-centrica-launches-spirit-energy-bayerngas|title=British Gas owner Centrica has launched a new company|last=Key|first=Alys|date=2017-12-11|access-date=2018-04-20|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420203005/http://www.cityam.com/277278/british-gas-owner-centrica-launches-spirit-energy-bayerngas|archive-date=20 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Senior management==\n[[Sam Laidlaw]] was the chief executive of Centrica between 1 July 2006 and 31 December 2014. In the 2010 financial year  Laidlaw received a salary of \u00a3941,000 and a bonus of \u00a3900,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sam Laidlaw: Executive Profile & Biography |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=1477130&ric=CNA.L |work=Bloomberg BusinessWeek |publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]] |accessdate=2 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Iain Conn]] was appointed Group Chief Executive of Centrica on 1 January 2015; he had previously been [[BP]]'s chief executive, downstream (BP's refining and marketing division) for seven years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centrica.com/about-us/governance/our-board-members/iain-conn|title=Iain Conn {{!}} Centrica plc|website=www.centrica.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\nGroup Chief Financial Officer Chris O'Shea was appointed Interim Group Chief Executive of Centrica on 17 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a0021f8a-6823-11ea-a3c9-1fe6fedcca75|publisher=FT.com|title=Centrica finance boss takes over as interim chief|language=en|date=17 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Greenwash===\n\nBritish Gas was accused of [[greenwashing]] in the advertising of its Zero Carbon tariff in January 2008, after the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] upheld a complaint about the 'greenest domestic tariff' claim.<ref>{{Cite news| url =http://www.asa.org.uk/asa/adjudications/Public/TF_ADJ_43903.htm| title =ASA Adjudication on British Gas Trading Ltd| publisher =ASA| date =30 January 2008| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20081204073847/http://www.asa.org.uk/asa/adjudications/Public/TF_ADJ_43903.htm| archivedate =4 December 2008| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Customer complaint response===\nIn July 2011, British Gas was fined \u00a32.5 million by the energy regulator [[Office of Gas and Electricity Markets|Ofgem]] for failing to deal properly with customer complaints.<ref name=\"gas-hits\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2011/jul/27/british-gas-unhappy-ofgem-fine|title=British Gas hits out at \u00a32.5m Ofgem fine|last=Insley|first=Jill|date=27 July 2011|work=The Guardian|location=London}}</ref>\n\nOfgem found that British Gas failed to re open complaints from customers who indicated they felt the matter was not resolved adequately, failed to provide sufficient information to complainants about the energy ombudsman service, and failed to deal properly with complaints from micro businesses because it had not implemented the necessary processes and practices.<ref name=\"gas-hits\"/>\n\nA spokesperson for British Gas said the company felt that finding it in breach of rules for failing to provide adequate information to consumers about the energy ombudsman was \"disproportionate to the mistake\".<ref name=\"gas-hits\"/>\n\nBritish Gas Business was fined \u00a31&nbsp;million in July 2011 after Ofgem's investigation found the company had misreported the amount of electricity supplied under the British government's renewables obligation.<ref name=\"gas-hits\"/> British Gas claims it spotted the problem \u2013 it said an over-reporting of the amount of renewable energy it was supplying caused by human error \u2013 and notified the regulator.<ref name=\"gas-hits\"/>\n\n===Political activity===\nCentrica entered the political arena in February 2014, by threatening an [[Capital strike|investment strike]] in response to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party's]] proposal for a [[Price controls|price freeze]]. [[Caroline Flint]], the shadow energy secretary, said: \"It is not acceptable for companies to threaten that the lights will go out because they don't want greater transparency, competition and accountability\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Rupert |last=Neate |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/feb/20/centrica-profit-down-571-million-2013 |title=Energy chief: political wrangling raises UK blackout risk &#124; Business |work=The Guardian |date=20 February 2014 |accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref> \n\nCentrica has also funded, in conjunction with [[Cuadrilla Resources]], the North West Energy Task Force<ref name=\"North West Energy Task Force About Us\">{{cite web |title=ABOUT US \u2013 North West Energy Task Force |url=http://www.nwenergy.org.uk:80/about-us |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609022944/http://www.nwenergy.org.uk:80/about-us |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 June 2016 |website=North West Energy Task Force |publisher=North West Energy Task Force |accessdate=15 October 2018 |date=9 June 2016}}</ref> which on 8 January 2015 organised an Open Letter to [[Lancashire County Council]] in support of fracking. This letter was signed by Jane Watson,<ref name=\"North West Energy Task Force Open Letter\">{{cite web |title=Lancashire business leaders to local council: \"Give shale a chance.\" \u2013 North West Energy Task Force |url=http://www.nwenergy.org.uk:80/lancashire_business_leaders_to_local_council_give_shale_a_chance |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616073508/http://www.nwenergy.org.uk:80/lancashire_business_leaders_to_local_council_give_shale_a_chance |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 June 2016 |website=North West Energy Task Force |publisher=North West Energy Task Force |accessdate=15 October 2018 |date=16 June 2016}}</ref> sister of [[Robert Altham]], the judge who sentenced three [[anti-fracking movement|anti-fracking]] protesters to jail in September 2018.<ref name=\"GAW\">{{cite news |last1=Gibb |first1=Frances |last2=Ames |first2=Jonathan |last3=Webster |first3=Ben |title=Robert Altham: Judge with oil links sent fracking protesters to jail |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/robert-altham-judge-with-oil-links-sent-fracking-protesters-to-jail-3b7znmts8 |work=The Times |issue=12 October 2018 |date=2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{UKPower}}\n{{Energy in the United Kingdom|companies}}\n{{FTSE 100 Index constituents}}\n{{Electricity generation in South East England}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Public utilities established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Utilities of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Natural gas companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Electric power companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Berkshire]]\n[[Category:British Royal Warrant holders]]\n[[Category:Centrica]]\n[[Category:Windsor, Berkshire]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1997]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name      =  Centrica plc\n| logo      =  Centrica logo.svg\n| type      = [[Public limited company]]\n| traded_as = {{lse|CNA}}<br />[[FTSE 100 Index|FTSE 100 Component]]\n| foundation        = {{start date and age|1997|02|17}}\n| location          = [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]], England, UK\n| key_people        = {{ubl|{{wd-chairperson}}|{{wd-ceo}}}}\n| industry          =  Utilities\n| products          =\n| revenue           =  {{decrease}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]26.825&nbsp;billion (2019)<ref name=prelims>{{cite web|url=https://www.centrica.com/media/4012/prelims-announcement-2019-final.pdf|title=Preliminary Results 2018 |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_income  = {{decrease}} \u00a30.901&nbsp;billion (2019)<ref name=prelims/>\n| net_income        =  {{decrease}} \u00a3(1.103)&nbsp;billion (2019)<ref name=prelims/>\n| num_employees     =\n| parent            =\n| subsid            =  See below\n| homepage          =  {{URL|http://www.centrica.com/}}\n| footnotes         =\n}}\n\n'''Centrica plc''' is a British [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] energy and services company with its headquarters in [[Windsor, Berkshire]]. Its principal activity is the [[Electricity supply|supply of electricity]] and [[Natural gas|gas]] to businesses and consumers in the United Kingdom, Ireland and North America.\n\nIt is the largest supplier of gas to domestic customers in the United Kingdom, and one of the largest suppliers of electricity, operating under the trading names [[Scottish Gas]] in Scotland and [[British Gas]] in England and Wales. It owns [[Bord Gais Energy|Bord G\u00e1is Energy]] in Ireland. It is also active in the provision of household services including plumbing.\n\nCentrica is listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]], and is a constituent of the [[FTSE 100 Index]].\n{{TOC limit|limit=3}}\n\n==History==\n\n===Historical origins===\nThe company has its historical origin in the [[Gas Light and Coke Company]] which incorporated in 1812. Over the next 137 years, it grew by acquisition of other gas companies to become the primary supplier of gas to [[Greater London]]. In 1949, under the [[Gas Act 1948]] the ownership of the company transferred to a government agency, [[North Thames Gas Board]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/search2?coll_id=1167&inst_id=14 |title=Gas, Light and Coke Company |last= |first= |date= |work=Archives in the M25 area |publisher=AIM25 |accessdate=}}</ref> The various area [[gas board]]s were merged into the national [[British Gas Corporation]] in 1973. The [[Gas Act 1986]] sold the company to private investors as [[British Gas plc]].<ref>{{cite web|title=30 SECOND GUIDE: Tell Sid|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/news/article-2072001/30-SECOND-GUIDE-Tell-Sid.html|date=2012-07-17|accessdate=2012-12-29}}</ref>\n\n===Origin===\nCentrica became a separate, distinct corporation on 17 February 1997, when [[British Gas plc]] split (demerged) to form three separate companies: Centrica plc, [[BG Group plc|BG plc]] and [[National Grid plc|Transco plc]].  Centrica took over gas sales and gas trading, services and retail businesses, together with the gas production operations in the North and South Morecambe gas fields ([[Rampside Gas Terminal]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12078257.Green_light_for_split_British_Gas_divides_with_aim_of_conquering_market/|title=Green light for split British Gas divides with aim of conquering market|date=13 February 1997|newspaper=Herald Scotland|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Centrica's supplier monopoly for gas came to an end. Centrica maintained the British Gas retail brand but is only allowed to use this brand name in the United Kingdom. The electricity market also opened up to competition and, through the British Gas brand, the company started supplying its first domestic electricity customers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theenergyshop.com/HomeEnergy/advice-guides-deregulationHistory#.Vu77iPmLQdU|title=An alternative history of energy deregulation and energy price comparison in the UK|publisher=The energy shop|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===1998 to 2010===\nAt the end of 1998, under CEO Sir Roy Gardner and Finance Director Mark Clare, Centrica attempted to diversify \u2013 firstly by developing the Goldfish credit card,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/1476617.stm |title=Centrica pays \u00a385m for Goldfish data |work=BBC News |date=6 August 2001 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> then in July 1999, by acquiring the [[The Automobile Association|AA]] for \u00a31.1&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/the_company_file/386200.stm |title=Power firm buys AA |work=BBC News |date=5 July 1999 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> In July 2001, Centrica further diversified with the opportunistic purchase of OneTel in the United Kingdom, a residential telecoms operator.<ref>{{cite news|first=Richard |last=Wray |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2001/jul/04/citynews.media |title=Centrica purchase builds up telecoms business |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date= 4 July 2001|accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nSoon afterwards, Centrica acquired the Dyno franchise group (best known for its [[Dyno-Rod]] drains unblocking service).<ref>{{cite web|author=This is Money|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/news/article.html?in_article_id=317904&in_page_id=2 |title=Dyno-Rod in Centrica's sights? |work=Daily Mail |date=16 August 2004 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Centrica also moved into the North American energy supply market, through the acquisition of the Canada-based company [[Direct Energy]] in July 2000, for \u00a3406&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/business/energy-and-utilities/centrica_plans_163_289m_refinancing_move_at_enbridge_1_858131|title=Centrica plans \u00a3289m refinancing move at Enbridge|accessdate=11 February 2012|work=The Scotsman|date=10 December 2002}}</ref> Direct Energy's operations were subsequently considerably expanded through a number of further acquisitions, including of [[Enbridge]] Services for \u00a3437&nbsp;million in January 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/business/energy-and-utilities/centrica_picks_up_an_extra_1_3m_canadian_customers_1_595243|title=Centrica picks up an extra 1.3m Canadian customers|accessdate=11 February 2012|work=The Scotsman|date=29 January 2002}}</ref>\n\nThis strategy of diversification changed in the middle of 2003, possibly under pressure from major city shareholders to deliver better returns and/or possibly anticipating pressure on the core energy supply business. The change of strategy started with the sale of the Goldfish business to Lloyds TSB Bank<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/globalassets/documents/investors/2003/2003aug1_goldfish_acquisition.pdf|title=Rough ruling and Goldfish sale boost Centrica]|accessdate=2015-01-15|publisher=Lloyds PLC}}</ref> (who subsequently sold it to Morgan Stanley Bank International Limited).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/4544520.stm |title=Lloyds TSB sells Goldfish brand |work=BBC News |date=20 December 2005 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThen, in July 2004, Centrica sold the AA to two private equity firms; Luxembourgish [[CVC Capital Partners|CVC]] and British [[Permira]] for \u00a31.75&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3855635.stm |title=Centrica gets bumper price for AA |work=BBC News |date=1 July 2004 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Centrica then acquired [[Dyno-Rod]] in October 2004.<ref name=\"Centrica acquires Dyno-Rod\">{{cite web|title=Centrica acquires Dyno-Rod|url=http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=1090&newsid=444|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119023812/http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=1090&newsid=444|archive-date=19 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Then, in December 2005, Centrica sold their OneTel business to Carphone Warehouse.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/4541148.stm |title=Carphone buys One-tel for \u00a3132m |work=BBC News |date=19 December 2005 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nSince 2005, Centrica has declared a strategy of consolidating within the energy sector, upstream and downstream, including expanding operations overseas. New chairman Roger Carr replaced retiring chairman Sir Michael Perry in 2005, whilst new CEO Sam Laidlaw picked up the reins from retiring CEO Sir Roy Gardner in March 2006.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://businesswriter.wordpress.com/2006/03/14/centricas-new-chief-executive-is-outsider-sam-laidlaw/ |title=Centrica's new Chief Executive is outsider Sam Laidlaw |publisher=Businesswriter.wordpress.com |date=14 March 2006 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006, it was rumoured that the Russian state owned utility company [[Gazprom]] was seeking a takeover of Centrica. This created controversy in the media, while the Department for Trade and Industry stated any deal would be subject to \"intense scrutiny\". [[Tony Blair]] announced in April that he would not block any potential deal.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2937583/Gazprom-free-to-bid-for-Centrica.html Gazprom free to bid for Centrica] ''The Daily Telegraph'', 26 April 2006</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, the company acquired the Caythorpe gas producing field near [[Bridlington]] to use for storage purposes.<ref>{{cite news|date=25 September 2008 |url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/businessnews/Centrica-buys-old-gas-field.4526357.jp |title=Centrica buys old gas field |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> It also agreed to buy 20% of [[British Energy]] from [[EDF Energy|EDF]], financing this with a \u00a32.2&nbsp;billion, 3 for 8 [[rights issue]].<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7701407.stm|publisher=BBC|title=Centrica looks to raise \u00a32.2bn|date=31 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=39&newsid=1845|publisher=Centrica|title=Approval from the OFT of Centrica's acquisition of 20% of British Energy from EDF|date=7 August 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815005829/http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=39&newsid=1845|archivedate=15 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The rights issue offered shares at 160 pence per share and closed on 12 December 2008.<ref>{{cite paper |title=Provisional Allotment Letter |author=Centrica |date=November 2008}}</ref> In August 2009, Centrica took over [[Venture Production]], a North Sea gas producer.<ref>{{Cite news| url =http://www.centrica.co.uk/index.asp?pageid=39&newsid=1856| title =Venture offer \u2013 Centrica achieves 58.7 per cent. level| publisher =Centrica Plc| date =24 August 2009| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090828002117/http://www.centrica.co.uk/index.asp?pageid=39&newsid=1856| archivedate =28 August 2009| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2010 to 2019===\nOn 13 June 2010 Centrica, through Direct Energy, acquired Clockwork Home Services. Combining with the existing energy offer made Centrica the largest provider of heating and cooling, plumbing and electrical services in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.achrnews.com/articles/114114-june-10-2010-clockwork-home-services-sold-to-direct-energy|title=Clockwork Home Services Sold to Direct Energy|date=10 June 2010|website=The News|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> On 17 November 2010, Centrica acquired the assets of heat pump installation company Cool Planet Technologies Ltd. for \u00a30.5 million in cash. This aimed to boost the company's strategy of developing a broad range of low carbon technologies and advice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.energylivenews.com/2010/11/18/british-gas-buys-cool-planet-technologies/|title=British Gas buys Cool Planet Technologies|publisher=Energy Live News|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, Centrica signed a \u00a32&nbsp;billion three-year contract with Qatargas for the purchase of 2.4 million tonnes a year of liquefied natural gas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/centrica-in-2bn-qatar-gas-deal-2223287.html|title=Centrica in \u00a32bn Qatar gas deal|accessdate=11 February 2012|work=The Independent|date=23 February 2011}}</ref> In March 2011, Centrica agreed the sale of the electricity and gas supply business of its Netherlands-based subsidiary [[Oxxio]] to Eneco BV for \u20ac72&nbsp;million (\u00a363&nbsp;million) in cash. The sale completed Centrica's exit from the supply of electricity and gas in Continental Europe, following the earlier disposal of its supply businesses in Belgium and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2011/02/centrica_hopes_to_sell_energy/|title=Centrica hopes to sell energy firm Oxxio this year|date=24 January 2011|publisher=Dutch News|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Centrica agreed to buy $1.6 billion stakes of 8 fields on the Norwegian continental shelf from [[Statoil]] ASA. In a second deal, Centrica agreed to buy 5 billion cubic meters a year gas from the same company from 2015 to 2025 as equal to 5% of gas consumption in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-11-21/centrica-agrees-to-buy-norwegian-gas-stakes-from-statoil-for-1-6-billion.html |title=Centrica Agrees to Buy Norwegian Gas Fields From Statoil for $1.6 Billion |date=22 November 2011 | work=Bloomberg |first1=Eduard |last1=Gismatullin |first2=Kari |last2=Lundgren}}</ref> Centrica's Germany based trading division ''Centrica Energie GmbH'' was closed in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.centrica-energie.de/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070225102739/http://www.centrica-energie.de/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 February 2007 |title=Centrica Energie GmbH |publisher=Centrica-energie.de |accessdate=21 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, it was announced that Centrica would acquire the energy marketing unit of [[Hess Corporation]] for $1.03 billion.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/07/30/us-centrica-idUSBRE96T0MA20130730| title=Hess to sell Energy Marketing unit to UK's Centrica for $1.03 billion | first=Swetha |last=Gopinath |first2=Sarah|last2=Young | agency=Reuters | date=30 July 2013}}</ref> In March 2014, Centrica acquired the retail arm and other assets belonging to Ireland's state owned [[Bord G\u00e1is]] for a fee of around \u20ac1.1 billion.<ref>{{cite news|title= Centrica buys Irish energy supplier as profits sink at home|work= Reuters|date=25 March 2014|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/25/us-centrica-bordgais-idUSBREA2O0F420140325|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Centrica entered into joint venture arrangements with [[Tullow Oil]] to explore for oil in the [[South Lokichar Basin]] in [[Kenya]]. In August 2014, Tullow, the operator, revealed significant oil discoveries had been made in the Etom 1 exploration well and testing block 10BB, which expanded the already proven South Lokichar Basin \"significantly northwards,\" taking in an additional 247 km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=\"TullowKenya\">{{cite news|title=More oil discovery announced by Tullow in Kenya|url=http://www.kenyastar.com/index.php/sid/225199123|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=28 August 2014|publisher=Kenya Star}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Centrica established [[Hive Connected Home|Hive]] as part of its Connected Home offering, building on its Remote Heating Control service provided through its British Gas subsidiary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/hive-2-begins-major-push-by-british-gas-into-smart-home-range-connected-devices-1510864|title=Hive 2 begins major push by British Gas into smart home with range of connected devices|website=International Business Times|date=16 July 2015|accessdate=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, in light of significantly changed circumstances, a fundamental strategic review was launched. This focused on outlook and sources of growth; portfolio mix and capital intensity; operating capability and efficiency; and Group financial framework. The review was a thorough and rigorous analysis of the Group's prospects, led by Centrica's senior management. It concluded that Centrica's strength lay in being a customer-facing business and that all activities and priorities would focus on meeting customers' changing needs. The shape of the Group would be reworked to reflect this, including a Group-wide efficiency programme that would reduce employee numbers by around 6,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/jul/30/british-gas-owner-centrica-cuts-thousands-of-jobs-group-shakeup|title=British Gas owner Centrica cuts thousands of jobs|date=30 July 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlso in February 2015, under its British Gas brand, Centrica completed the acquisition of AlertMe, a connected home company based in the United Kingdom that provided innovative energy management products and services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/16c90ea4-b38d-11e4-a45f-00144feab7de|title=British Gas buys 'smart home' tech company AlertMe|newspaper=Financial Times|date=13 February 2019|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> In November 2015, Direct Energy also acquired Panoramic Power, a provider of device level energy management technology, for $60 million (\u00a339 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/read/direct-energy-buys-panoramic-power-for-60m|title=Direct Energy Buys Panoramic Power for $60M|date=16 November 2015|publisher=Green Tech Media|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Centrica acquired Neas Energy A/S (Neas), one of Europe's providers of energy management and revenue optimisation services for decentralised third-party owned assets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/neas-energy-ma-centrica/centrica-buys-denmark-energy-management-firm-neas-for-170-mln-stg-idUKFWN17O043|title=Centrica buys Denmark energy management firm Neas for 170 mln stg|date=21 April 2016|work=Reuters|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> It also acquired ENER-G Cogen International Limited (\"ENER-G Cogen\"), an established supplier and operator of combined heat and power (CHP) systems and REstore NV, Europe's demand response aggregator.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/read/centrica-buys-ener-g-cogen-for-212-million|title=Centrica Buys ENER-G Cogen for $212 Million|date=23 May 2016|publisher=Green Tech Media|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, it was announced that the CQ Energy Canada Partnership, the Canadian E&P joint venture in which Centrica plc owned a 60% interest, was to be sold to a consortium comprising MIE Holdings Corporation, The Can-China Global Resource Fund and Mercuria for a purchase price of C$722 million (\u00a3413 million) in cash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.energylivenews.com/2017/06/12/centrica-sells-240m-stake-in-canadian-oil-and-gas-firm/|title=Centrica sells \u00a3240m stake in Canadian oil and gas firm|publisher=Energy Live News|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 2017, the company agreed to sell its operational Langage and South Humber Bank combined cycle gas turbine power stations, with a combined capacity of 2.3GW, to EP UK Investments Ltd for \u00a3318million in cash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eppowereurope.cz/en/tiskove-zpravy/eph-buy-langage-south-humber-bank-gas-fired-power-stations-centrica/|title=EPH to buy Langage and South Humber Bank gas-fired power stations from Centrica|date=21 June 2017|publisher=EP Power Europe|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 2017 Centrica launched Spirit Energy as a joint venture with German energy and infrastructure firm Stadtwerke M\u00fcnchen (SWM).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/energyterminal/natural-gas/centrica-launches-spirit-energy-ep-joint-venture/15914|title=Centrica launches Spirit Energy E&P joint venture|publisher=AA Energy|date=11 December 2017|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, the Competition & Markets Authority agreed to grant Centrica plc and Centrica Storage Limited's (CSL's) request to be released from the [[Rough (facility)|Rough]] Undertakings. CSL decided that it could no longer operate Rough as a storage facility as the facility was no longer capable of safe injection operations due to the age and condition of the asset, and that due to the economics of seasonal storage and the cost of refurbishing or rebuilding the facility, neither pathway would be economic.<ref name=rough>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/cma-cases/rough-gas-storage-facility-review-of-undertakings|title=Rough gas storage facility: review of undertakings|date=17 October 2017|publisher=Competition and Markets Authority|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Since 2020===\nIn 2020, following the onset of the 2020 [[coronavirus pandemic]], offices and factories shut and energy use decreased sharply, and the financial problems caused by the pandemic among Centrica's customers will inevitably lead to bad debts. Analysts dropped their estimate of Centrica's earnings for 2020, 2021 and 2022 by 30%. Centrica paused its search for a buyer for its 69% stake in Spirit Energy. The share price in April reached a record low value of \u00a30.30, valuing the company at less than half of its net debt of nearly \u00a34b.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/nils-pratley-on-finance/2020/apr/22/british-gas-owner-needs-more-than-cost-cutting-and-energy-prices-prayer |title=British Gas owner needs more than cost-cutting and energy prices prayer |newspaper=The Guardian |author= |date= 22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n===Organisation===\nCentrica's operations are principally focused on the supply of electricity and gas to businesses and consumers in the United Kingdom and North America. They are organised as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centrica.com/about-us/what-we-do/centrica-business|title=Centrica Business|publisher=Centrica|accessdate=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n* Businesses in the United Kingdom, including [[British Gas]] which supplies gas, electricity and services to residential and business customers\n* Distributed Energy & Power which supports large energy users\n* North America Business including [[Direct Energy]] which supplies gas, electricity and services to residential and business customers\n* Energy Marketing & Trading which provides risk management services\n* Central Power Generation, which has a 20% interest in 8 power stations\n\n=== Shareholdings ===\nIn May 2009, Centrica purchased a 20% stake in nuclear power generator [[British Energy]] from [[EDF Energy]]. The company now produces 14.3% of its electricity from nuclear plants (the second highest rate in the United Kingdom), helping it to achieve the lowest carbon emissions of the major providers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electricity-guide.org.uk/fuel-mix.html |title=Fuel Mix Information |publisher=Electricity-guide.org.uk |date= |accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref> Centrica has also acquired an option to purchase a 20% stake in EDF's subsidiary, [[NNB Generation Company]] (NNB GenCo).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=39&newsid=1783 |title=Centrica to invest in EDF nuclear business in the UK |publisher=Centrica.com |date=31 December 2013 |accessdate=21 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125074949/http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=39 |archivedate=25 November 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Centrica launched a new company as a joint venture with German energy and infrastructure firm [[Stadtwerke M\u00fcnchen]] (SWM). Spirit Energy, an exploration and production (E&P) company, is the result of a combination of Centrica's E&P business and [[Bayerngas Norge]] AS, which was formerly majority-owned by SWM. Centrica plc owns 69% of Spirit Energy, with Bayerngas Norge's former shareholders, led by SWM and Bayerngas GmbH, owning 31%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cityam.com/277278/british-gas-owner-centrica-launches-spirit-energy-bayerngas|title=British Gas owner Centrica has launched a new company|last=Key|first=Alys|date=2017-12-11|access-date=2018-04-20|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420203005/http://www.cityam.com/277278/british-gas-owner-centrica-launches-spirit-energy-bayerngas|archive-date=20 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Senior management==\n[[Sam Laidlaw]] was the chief executive of Centrica between 1 July 2006 and 31 December 2014. In the 2010 financial year  Laidlaw received a salary of \u00a3941,000 and a bonus of \u00a3900,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sam Laidlaw: Executive Profile & Biography |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=1477130&ric=CNA.L |work=Bloomberg BusinessWeek |publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]] |accessdate=2 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Iain Conn]] was appointed Group Chief Executive of Centrica on 1 January 2015; he had previously been [[BP]]'s chief executive, downstream (BP's refining and marketing division) for seven years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centrica.com/about-us/governance/our-board-members/iain-conn|title=Iain Conn {{!}} Centrica plc|website=www.centrica.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\nChris Group Chief Financial Officer O'Shea was appointed Interim Group Chief Executive of Centrica on 17 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a0021f8a-6823-11ea-a3c9-1fe6fedcca75|publisher=FT.com|title=Centrica finance boss takes over as interim chief|language=en|date=17 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Greenwash===\n\nBritish Gas was accused of [[greenwashing]] in the advertising of its Zero Carbon tariff in January 2008, after the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] upheld a complaint about the 'greenest domestic tariff' claim.<ref>{{Cite news| url =http://www.asa.org.uk/asa/adjudications/Public/TF_ADJ_43903.htm| title =ASA Adjudication on British Gas Trading Ltd| publisher =ASA| date =30 January 2008| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20081204073847/http://www.asa.org.uk/asa/adjudications/Public/TF_ADJ_43903.htm| archivedate =4 December 2008| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Customer complaint response===\nIn July 2011, British Gas was fined \u00a32.5 million by the energy regulator [[Office of Gas and Electricity Markets|Ofgem]] for failing to deal properly with customer complaints.<ref name=\"gas-hits\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2011/jul/27/british-gas-unhappy-ofgem-fine|title=British Gas hits out at \u00a32.5m Ofgem fine|last=Insley|first=Jill|date=27 July 2011|work=The Guardian|location=London}}</ref>\n\nOfgem found that British Gas failed to re open complaints from customers who indicated they felt the matter was not resolved adequately, failed to provide sufficient information to complainants about the energy ombudsman service, and failed to deal properly with complaints from micro businesses because it had not implemented the necessary processes and practices.<ref name=\"gas-hits\"/>\n\nA spokesperson for British Gas said the company felt that finding it in breach of rules for failing to provide adequate information to consumers about the energy ombudsman was \"disproportionate to the mistake\".<ref name=\"gas-hits\"/>\n\nBritish Gas Business was fined \u00a31&nbsp;million in July 2011 after Ofgem's investigation found the company had misreported the amount of electricity supplied under the British government's renewables obligation.<ref name=\"gas-hits\"/> British Gas claims it spotted the problem \u2013 it said an over-reporting of the amount of renewable energy it was supplying caused by human error \u2013 and notified the regulator.<ref name=\"gas-hits\"/>\n\n===Political activity===\nCentrica entered the political arena in February 2014, by threatening an [[Capital strike|investment strike]] in response to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party's]] proposal for a [[Price controls|price freeze]]. [[Caroline Flint]], the shadow energy secretary, said: \"It is not acceptable for companies to threaten that the lights will go out because they don't want greater transparency, competition and accountability\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Rupert |last=Neate |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/feb/20/centrica-profit-down-571-million-2013 |title=Energy chief: political wrangling raises UK blackout risk &#124; Business |work=The Guardian |date=20 February 2014 |accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref> \n\nCentrica has also funded, in conjunction with [[Cuadrilla Resources]], the North West Energy Task Force<ref name=\"North West Energy Task Force About Us\">{{cite web |title=ABOUT US \u2013 North West Energy Task Force |url=http://www.nwenergy.org.uk:80/about-us |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609022944/http://www.nwenergy.org.uk:80/about-us |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 June 2016 |website=North West Energy Task Force |publisher=North West Energy Task Force |accessdate=15 October 2018 |date=9 June 2016}}</ref> which on 8 January 2015 organised an Open Letter to [[Lancashire County Council]] in support of fracking. This letter was signed by Jane Watson,<ref name=\"North West Energy Task Force Open Letter\">{{cite web |title=Lancashire business leaders to local council: \"Give shale a chance.\" \u2013 North West Energy Task Force |url=http://www.nwenergy.org.uk:80/lancashire_business_leaders_to_local_council_give_shale_a_chance |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616073508/http://www.nwenergy.org.uk:80/lancashire_business_leaders_to_local_council_give_shale_a_chance |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 June 2016 |website=North West Energy Task Force |publisher=North West Energy Task Force |accessdate=15 October 2018 |date=16 June 2016}}</ref> sister of [[Robert Altham]], the judge who sentenced three [[anti-fracking movement|anti-fracking]] protesters to jail in September 2018.<ref name=\"GAW\">{{cite news |last1=Gibb |first1=Frances |last2=Ames |first2=Jonathan |last3=Webster |first3=Ben |title=Robert Altham: Judge with oil links sent fracking protesters to jail |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/robert-altham-judge-with-oil-links-sent-fracking-protesters-to-jail-3b7znmts8 |work=The Times |issue=12 October 2018 |date=2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{UKPower}}\n{{Energy in the United Kingdom|companies}}\n{{FTSE 100 Index constituents}}\n{{Electricity generation in South East England}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Public utilities established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Utilities of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Natural gas companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Electric power companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Berkshire]]\n[[Category:British Royal Warrant holders]]\n[[Category:Centrica]]\n[[Category:Windsor, Berkshire]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1997]]\n", "name_user": "Pol098", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSenior management", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centrica"}
{"title_page": "Greatest Hits (Queen album)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Greatest Hits\n| type       = greatest\n| artist     = [[Queen (band)|Queen]]\n| cover      = Queen Greatest Hits.png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Original 1981 edition\n| released   = 26 October 1981\n| recorded   = 1974\u20131980 (1981 UK edition (EMI) & 2011 UK edition (Island) & 1994 US edition) <br /> 1972\u20131981 (1981 US & Canada edition) <br /> 1974\u20131981 (1981 Japan edition & 2011 Japan Reissue edition) <br /> 1972\u20131983 (1992 US edition (Hollywood Records)) <br /> 1973\u20131982 (2004 US edition (''Greatest Hits: We Will Rock You''))\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length     = 58:19 (UK edition)\n| label      = {{ubl|[[EMI Records|EMI]]|[[Elektra Records|Elektra]]}}\n| producer   = Queen, various\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Queen (band)|Queen]]\n | type       = greatest\n | prev_title =\n | prev_year  =\n | title      = Greatest Hits\n | year       = 1981\n | next_title = [[The Complete Works (Queen album)|The Complete Works]]\n | next_year  = 1985\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = greatest\n | cover   = RedGreatestHitsQuennalbumcover.png\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = 1992 US edition\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Greatest Hits''''' is a [[compilation album]] by the British rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]], released worldwide on 26 October 1981.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=17 October 1981|title=Record News|magazine=[[NME]]|page=48}}</ref> The album consisted of Queen's biggest hits since their first chart appearance in 1974 with \"[[Seven Seas of Rhye]]\", up to their 1980 hit \"[[Flash (Queen song)|Flash]]\" (though in some countries \"[[Under Pressure]]\", the band's 1981 chart-topper with [[David Bowie]], was included). There was no universal track listing or cover art for the album, and each territory's tracks were dependent on what singles had been released there and which were successful. In 1991, the US version of the album ''[[Classic Queen]]'' was released following the band's rekindled in popularity in the nation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''Greatest Hits'' was a commercial success worldwide with sales of over 25 million copies, making it one of the [[List of best-selling albums|best-selling albums of all time]]. It reached number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]], spending four weeks at the top and sold consistently well throughout the 1980s, becoming the fourth-biggest selling album of the decade. The single \"Under Pressure\", Queen's collaboration with David Bowie which was released the same week as ''Greatest Hits'', also topped the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nAs of October 2019, ''Greatest Hits'' has spent 868 weeks on the UK Albums Chart and has been certified [[BPI certification|20\u00d7 platinum]] with sales of over 6 million copies, making it the [[List of best-selling albums in the United Kingdom|best-selling album of all time in the UK]]. Among the [[Billboard 200#Most weeks on the chart|longest charting albums in the US]], as of April 2020, it has spent 380 weeks on the ''Billboard'' 200. It has been certified [[RIAA certification|8\u00d7 platinum]] in the US, 15\u00d7 platinum in Australia, 10\u00d7 platinum in New Zealand, and 3\u00d7 platinum in Canada. Following the release of the Queen biopic ''[[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]]'' in 2018, it re-entered the charts of countries worldwide.\n\n== Release ==\nThere was no universal track listing or cover art for the ''Greatest Hits'' album, and each territory's tracks were dependent on what singles were released there and what tracks charted. In some cases, despite the band's popularity, not enough songs were issued as singles to fill a compilation album, and a few album tracks were used as filler. Some examples of these were \"[[Sweet Lady (Queen song)|Sweet Lady]]\" and \"[[Love of My Life (Queen song)|Love of My Life]]\", neither was released as a single in any country, but appear on some regions' ''1981 Hits'' release. In the UK and the US, where solid numbers could be collected, the album included only top 20 hits.\n\nThe US ended up with its original edit of Queen's first single release, \"[[Keep Yourself Alive]]\", which had been re-released in the US in 1975 (original release was 1973) after the success of \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\". The US version also added \"[[Under Pressure]]\", Queen's collaboration with [[David Bowie]], which was released the same week as ''Greatest Hits'' and subsequently topped the [[UK Singles Chart]] and reached the top ten in many charts around the world. However, the song was not included on the European versions of ''Greatest Hits'' \u2013 according to Queen's business manager Jim Beach, this was because the longer manufacturing time required to press records in Europe meant that several hundred thousand copies of the album had already been pressed up before the song had been recorded.<ref name=\"Billboard19811017\">{{cite magazine |first=Paul |last=Grein |title=Row over Rent-Only Plan for Queen Vid |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |pages=3 & 84 |date=17 October 1981}}</ref>\n\nIn Argentina and Brazil, the LP edition included the same list of UK Greatest Hits minus \"[[Seven Seas of Rhye]]\", and including \"Love of My Life\" ([[Live Killers]] version). CD version is the same as the British.\n\nThe cover photo that appeared on the UK and US release was taken by [[Lord Snowdon]] at his home studio using only natural light. For the 1981 release the photo was skewed but later presented as it was originally taken for the 2011 re-release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brianmay.com/brian/brianssb/brianssbjan17a.html#05|title=January 2017|website=www.brianmay.com|access-date=14 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/en/the-band/discography/greatest-hits/|title=Greatest Hits|website=Queen official website|access-date=14 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, Queen sought to issue a [[Greatest Hits II (Queen album)|second ''Greatest Hits'']] collection worldwide, this time with a standard track listing. However, the band had just changed record labels in the US, from Capitol to [[Hollywood Records]], who were keen on a massive promotion of the band's back catalogue. The problem was that Elektra still held the US rights to that first 1981 collection (despite being Hollywood's US licensee). Hollywood Records decided to not release ''Greatest Hits II'' to the US market, but instead created their own collection, ''[[Classic Queen]]'' (1992), peaking at number four.<ref name=\":0\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=hxAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8&dq=queen+waynes+world#v=onepage Billboard 25 Jul 1992] p.8. ''Billboard''. Retrieved 30 May 2011</ref> This compilation was made up of tracks such as \"Bohemian Rhapsody\", \"Keep Yourself Alive\" and \"Under Pressure\" (which had already appeared on the Elektra 1981 ''Hits'' collection) as well as newer tracks (\"[[A Kind of Magic (song)|A Kind of Magic]]\" and \"[[Radio Ga Ga]]\").<ref name=\"MTVClassicQueen\">[http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/queen/albums.jhtml?albumId=72769 Queen Album: Classic Queen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227021940/http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/queen/albums.jhtml?albumId=72769 |date=27 February 2008 }} MTV. Retrieved 30 May 2011</ref> Some tracks were not even singles in the US (\"[[One Year of Love (song)|One Year of Love]]\") or anywhere (\"[[Stone Cold Crazy]]\").<ref name=\"MTVClassicQueen\" /> Though well received, this collection would eventually pose the problem of overlapping track lists in the future.\n\nHollywood Records, later that year, re-released a companion collection ''Greatest Hits'' with similar artwork (on a red background, where ''Classic Queen'' was on royal blue). Commonly referred to as the ''Red Greatest Hits'', it features most of the '70s tracks absent from ''Classic Queen'' (including \"Another One Bites the Dust\" [1980], \"We Will Rock You\", \"We Are the Champions\" and \"Killer Queen\"). In 2004, to promote the Las Vegas production of the musical ''We Will Rock You'', Hollywood Records released ''Greatest Hits: We Will Rock You Edition'' which was the UK ''Greatest Hits'' with three bonus tracks.\n\n== ''Greatest Flix'' and ''Greatest Pix'' ==\nThe release of ''Greatest Hits'' was accompanied simultaneously by ''Greatest Flix'', a 60-minute compilation released on [[VHS]] video and [[LaserDisc]] of all the videos Queen had made up until that point in chronological order, and ''Greatest Pix'', a 96-page paperback book edited by [[Jacques Lowe]] which featured photos of the band taken by [[Neal Preston]].<ref name=\"Billboard19811017\" /> Although ''Greatest Flix'' only listed 17 videos on its sleeve, it contained two videos for \"We Will Rock You\". The video for \"Killer Queen\" had been shot especially for ''Greatest Flix'', as no video had been made for the song on its original release in 1974.<ref name=\"Billboard19811017\" />\n\n'''''Greatest Flix'''''\n#\"Killer Queen\"\n#\"Bohemian Rhapsody\"\n#\"You're My Best Friend\"\n#\"Somebody to Love\"\n#\"Tie Your Mother Down\"\n#\"We Are the Champions\"\n#\"We Will Rock You\"\n#\"We Will Rock You (Live)\"\n#\"Spread Your Wings\"\n#\"Bicycle Race\"\n#\"Fat Bottomed Girls\"\n#\"Don't Stop Me Now\"\n#\"Love of My Life (Live)\"\n#\"Crazy Little Thing Called Love\"\n#\"Save Me\"\n#\"Play the Game\"\n#\"Another One Bites the Dust\"\n#\"Flash\"\n\nNote: On the sleeve notes of the video, \"We Will Rock You\" is incorrectly listed before \"We Are the Champions\".\n\n== Critical reception and legacy ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\" />\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2Score = B+<ref name=\"EW\" />\n| rev3 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/queen/albumguide |title=Queen: Album Guide |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=20 February 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204113916/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/queen/albumguide |archivedate=4 December 2011}}</ref>\n}}\nInitial reviews of the album in the British music press were negative. In ''[[NME]]'' [[Barney Hoskyns]] said, \"All of [their songs], besides 'Another One Bites the Dust', are quite repulsive, unbelievably crass insults to their respective genres and uniformly vulgar music. It was only when Queen took vulgarity to its absolute limit that they stood out.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Barney |last=Hoskyns |authorlink=Barney Hoskyns |title=Queen \u2013 ''Greatest Hits'' |magazine=[[NME]] |page=36 |date=31 October 1981}}</ref> ''[[Melody Maker]]''{{'}}s [[Adam Sweeting]] stated, \"I've never been the slightest bit interested in Queen's ridiculous pomposity and Freddie just makes me snigger, but I suppose songs like 'Killer Queen' are sort of catchy, while anything as preposterous as 'We Will Rock You' deserves an award if only for bad taste\".<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Adam |last=Sweeting |authorlink=Adam Sweeting |title=Queen \u2013 ''Greatest Hits'' |magazine=[[Melody Maker]] |page=18 |date=31 October 1981}}</ref>\n\nHowever, retrospective reviews have rated the album higher: [[Ira Robbins]] gave ''Greatest Hits'' a B+ rating in ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' upon its reissue in 1992,<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,312359,00.html|title=Greatest Hits Review|last=Robbins|first=Ira|authorlink=Ira Robbins|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=13 November 1992|accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref> and William Ruhlmann of [[AllMusic]] awarded the record four and a half stars out of five.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |first=William |last=Ruhlmann |title=''Greatest Hits'' (1981) \u2013 Queen |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/greatest-hits-1981-mw0000939949 |website=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> In an interview in 2003 as part of the [[Arte]] television programme ''Music Planet 2Nite'', [[Radiohead]] guitarist [[Ed O'Brien]] hailed the album as \"impeccable\" and \"absolutely genius\".<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Radiohead live at Le R\u00e9servoir (Paris, France)|series=Music Planet 2nite|network=[[Arte]]|minutes=26:34|date=3 July 2003|quote=Queen did their Greatest Hits, and the first one is impeccable, isn't it? It's absolutely genius.}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nIn the UK, ''Greatest Hits'' debuted at number two on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and climbed to number one the following week, spending four weeks at the top. The album continued to sell well throughout the 1980s, appearing on several UK year-end charts, and by the end of the decade it had become the fourth-biggest selling album in the UK during the 1980s, with sales of over 1.9 million copies.<ref name=\"RM19891216\">{{cite magazine |first=Alan |last=Jones |title=Chartfile |magazine=[[Record Mirror]] |page=45 |date=16 December 1989}}</ref> By 2006, ''Greatest Hits'' had become the [[List of best-selling albums in the United Kingdom|best-selling album in the UK]] and the first album to sell more than five million copies there.<ref>{{cite news |title=Queen head all-time sales chart |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6151050.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=16 November 2006 |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> In February 2014, it was confirmed by the [[Official Charts Company]] that ''Greatest Hits'' had become the first album in the UK to sell over six million copies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen's Greatest Hits becomes first album to sell 6 million in the UK |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/queens-greatest-hits-becomes-first-album-to-sell-6-million-in-the-uk__3758/ |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Queen reach six million album sales in UK |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-26121239 |work=BBC News |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> The same year ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' stated one in three families in the UK owns a copy.<ref>{{cite news |title=Queen's Greatest Hits is first album to sell 6 million UK copies |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/10629578/Queens-Greatest-Hits-is-first-album-to-sell-6-million-UK-copies.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref> As of February 2019 the album has spent a total of 861 weeks on the UK Albums Chart.<ref name=\"UKchart\" />\n\nIn the US the album sold moderately well on initial release in 1981, being certified platinum,<ref name=\"RIAA\" /> and peaked at number 11 on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart on its reissue in 1992.<ref name=\"Billboard200\" /> However, it has since been certified eight times platinum for sales of eight million copies, making it the band's best-selling album there.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |title=Queen's 'Greatest Hits' Becomes First Album to Sell 6 Million in U.K. |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5901176/queen-greatest-hits-becomes-first-album-to-sell-6-million-in-uk |magazine=Billboard |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref> Among the [[Billboard 200#Most weeks on the chart|longest charting albums in the US]], as of April 2020 it has spent 380 weeks on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/queen/chart-history/billboard-200/song/177587|title=Queen Chart History (Billboard 200)|website=Billboard|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> It is also the band's best-selling album worldwide, with total sales of more than 25 million copies.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Pictures: 50 years of pop |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/in_depth/entertainment/2002/jubilee/popup/5.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=17 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |first=Sarah |last=Anderson |title=The 50 best-selling albums ever |url=https://www.nme.com/photos/the-50-best-selling-albums-ever-1419009 |magazine=NME |date=12 November 2010 |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\nThis section includes the track listings for the original ''Greatest Hits'' in its various forms. For other compilations, including the [[Greatest Hits II (Queen album)|second]] and [[Greatest Hits III (Queen album)|third]] ''Greatest Hits'' albums, see the relevant articles.\n\nOn the 17-track UK editions, [[Freddie Mercury]] was the writer of ten of the songs, [[Brian May]] five and [[John Deacon]] two. [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] had not written any songs that had been released as singles for the band at that point.\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 1981 UK edition (EMI) & 2011 UK edition (Island)<br />{{nobold|Has a photograph of the band as its cover.}}\n\n<br />Side one\n| title1          = [[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\n| note1           = from ''[[A Night at the Opera (Queen album)|A Night at the Opera]]'', 1975\n| writer1         = [[Freddie Mercury]]\n| length1         = 5:57\n| title2          = [[Another One Bites the Dust]]\n| note2           = from ''[[The Game (Queen album)|The Game]]'', 1980\n| writer2         = [[John Deacon]]\n| length2         = 3:36\n| title3          = [[Killer Queen]]\n| note3           = from ''[[Sheer Heart Attack]]'', 1974\n| writer3         = Mercury\n| length3         = 2:57\n| title4          = [[Fat Bottomed Girls]]\n| note4           = single version, from ''[[Jazz (Queen album)|Jazz]]'', 1978\n| writer4         = [[Brian May]]\n| length4         = 3:22\n| title5          = [[Bicycle Race]]\n| note5           = from ''Jazz'', 1978\n| writer5         = Mercury\n| length5         = 3:01\n| title6          = [[You're My Best Friend (Queen song)|You're My Best Friend]]\n| note6           = 