 Trident Studios]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Rockfield Studios]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Olympic Sound Studios]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Greatest Hits\n| type       = greatest\n| artist     = [[Queen (band)|Queen]]\n| cover      = Queen Greatest Hits.png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Original 1981 edition\n| released   = 26 October 1981\n| recorded   = 1974\u20131980 (1981 UK edition (EMI) & 2011 UK edition (Island) & 1994 US edition) <br /> 1972\u20131981 (1981 US & Canada edition) <br /> 1974\u20131981 (1981 Japan edition & 2011 Japan Reissue edition) <br /> 1972\u20131983 (1992 US edition (Hollywood Records)) <br /> 1973\u20131982 (2004 US edition (''Greatest Hits: We Will Rock You''))\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length     = 58:19 (UK edition)\n| label      = {{ubl|[[EMI Records|EMI]]|[[Elektra Records|Elektra]]}}\n| producer   = Queen, various\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Queen (band)|Queen]]\n | type       = greatest\n | prev_title =\n | prev_year  =\n | title      = Greatest Hits\n | year       = 1981\n | next_title = [[The Complete Works (Queen album)|The Complete Works]]\n | next_year  = 1985\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = greatest\n | cover   = RedGreatestHitsQuennalbumcover.png\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = 1992 US edition\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Greatest Hits''''' is a [[compilation album]] by the British rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]], released worldwide on 26 October 1981.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=17 October 1981|title=Record News|magazine=[[NME]]|page=48}}</ref> The album consisted of Queen's biggest hits since their first chart appearance in 1974 with \"[[Seven Seas of Rhye]]\", up to their 1980 hit \"[[Flash (Queen song)|Flash]]\" (though in some countries \"[[Under Pressure]]\", the band's 1981 chart-topper with [[David Bowie]], was included). There was no universal track listing or cover art for the album, and each territory's tracks were dependent on what singles had been released there and which were successful. In 1991, the US version of the album ''[[Classic Queen]]'' was released following the band's rekindled in popularity in the nation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''Greatest Hits'' was a commercial success worldwide with sales of over 25 million copies, making it one of the [[List of best-selling albums|best-selling albums of all time]]. It reached number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]], spending four weeks at the top and sold consistently well throughout the 1980s, becoming the fourth-biggest selling album of the decade. The single \"Under Pressure\", Queen's collaboration with David Bowie which was released the same week as ''Greatest Hits'', also topped the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nAs of October 2019, ''Greatest Hits'' has spent 868 weeks on the UK Albums Chart and has been certified [[BPI certification|20\u00d7 platinum]] with sales of over 6 million copies, making it the [[List of best-selling albums in the United Kingdom|best-selling album of all time in the UK]]. Among the [[Billboard 200#Most weeks on the chart|longest charting albums in the US]], as of April 2020, it has spent 380 weeks on the ''Billboard'' 200. It has been certified [[RIAA certification|8\u00d7 platinum]] in the US, 15\u00d7 platinum in Australia, 10\u00d7 platinum in New Zealand, and 3\u00d7 platinum in Canada. Following the release of the Queen biopic ''[[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]]'', it re-entered the charts of countries worldwide.\n\n== Release ==\nThere was no universal track listing or cover art for the ''Greatest Hits'' album, and each territory's tracks were dependent on what singles were released there and what tracks charted. In some cases, despite the band's popularity, not enough songs were issued as singles to fill a compilation album, and a few album tracks were used as filler. Some examples of these were \"[[Sweet Lady (Queen song)|Sweet Lady]]\" and \"[[Love of My Life (Queen song)|Love of My Life]]\", neither was released as a single in any country, but appear on some regions' ''1981 Hits'' release. In the UK and the US, where solid numbers could be collected, the album included only top 20 hits.\n\nThe US ended up with its original edit of Queen's first single release, \"[[Keep Yourself Alive]]\", which had been re-released in the US in 1975 (original release was 1973) after the success of \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\". The US version also added \"[[Under Pressure]]\", Queen's collaboration with [[David Bowie]], which was released the same week as ''Greatest Hits'' and subsequently topped the [[UK Singles Chart]] and reached the top ten in many charts around the world. However, the song was not included on the European versions of ''Greatest Hits'' \u2013 according to Queen's business manager Jim Beach, this was because the longer manufacturing time required to press records in Europe meant that several hundred thousand copies of the album had already been pressed up before the song had been recorded.<ref name=\"Billboard19811017\">{{cite magazine |first=Paul |last=Grein |title=Row over Rent-Only Plan for Queen Vid |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |pages=3 & 84 |date=17 October 1981}}</ref>\n\nIn Argentina and Brazil, the LP edition included the same list of UK Greatest Hits minus \"[[Seven Seas of Rhye]]\", and including \"Love of My Life\" ([[Live Killers]] version). CD version is the same as the British.\n\nThe cover photo that appeared on the UK and US release was taken by [[Lord Snowdon]] at his home studio using only natural light. For the 1981 release the photo was skewed but later presented as it was originally taken for the 2011 re-release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brianmay.com/brian/brianssb/brianssbjan17a.html#05|title=January 2017|website=www.brianmay.com|access-date=14 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/en/the-band/discography/greatest-hits/|title=Greatest Hits|website=Queen official website|access-date=14 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, Queen sought to issue a [[Greatest Hits II (Queen album)|second ''Greatest Hits'']] collection worldwide, this time with a standard track listing. However, the band had just changed record labels in the US, from Capitol to [[Hollywood Records]], who were keen on a massive promotion of the band's back catalogue. The problem was that Elektra still held the US rights to that first 1981 collection (despite being Hollywood's US licensee). Hollywood Records decided to not release ''Greatest Hits II'' to the US market, but instead created their own collection, ''[[Classic Queen]]'' (1992), peaking at number four.<ref name=\":0\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=hxAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8&dq=queen+waynes+world#v=onepage Billboard 25 Jul 1992] p.8. ''Billboard''. Retrieved 30 May 2011</ref> This compilation was made up of tracks such as \"Bohemian Rhapsody\", \"Keep Yourself Alive\" and \"Under Pressure\" (which had already appeared on the Elektra 1981 ''Hits'' collection) as well as newer tracks (\"[[A Kind of Magic (song)|A Kind of Magic]]\" and \"[[Radio Ga Ga]]\").<ref name=\"MTVClassicQueen\">[http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/queen/albums.jhtml?albumId=72769 Queen Album: Classic Queen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227021940/http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/queen/albums.jhtml?albumId=72769 |date=27 February 2008 }} MTV. Retrieved 30 May 2011</ref> Some tracks were not even singles in the US (\"[[One Year of Love (song)|One Year of Love]]\") or anywhere (\"[[Stone Cold Crazy]]\").<ref name=\"MTVClassicQueen\" /> Though well received, this collection would eventually pose the problem of overlapping track lists in the future.\n\nHollywood Records, later that year, re-released a companion collection ''Greatest Hits'' with similar artwork (on a red background, where ''Classic Queen'' was on royal blue). Commonly referred to as the ''Red Greatest Hits'', it features most of the '70s tracks absent from ''Classic Queen'' (including \"Another One Bites the Dust\" [1980], \"We Will Rock You\", \"We Are the Champions\" and \"Killer Queen\"). In 2004, to promote the Las Vegas production of the musical ''We Will Rock You'', Hollywood Records released ''Greatest Hits: We Will Rock You Edition'' which was the UK ''Greatest Hits'' with three bonus tracks.\n\n== ''Greatest Flix'' and ''Greatest Pix'' ==\nThe release of ''Greatest Hits'' was accompanied simultaneously by ''Greatest Flix'', a 60-minute compilation released on [[VHS]] video and [[LaserDisc]] of all the videos Queen had made up until that point in chronological order, and ''Greatest Pix'', a 96-page paperback book edited by [[Jacques Lowe]] which featured photos of the band taken by [[Neal Preston]].<ref name=\"Billboard19811017\" /> Although ''Greatest Flix'' only listed 17 videos on its sleeve, it contained two videos for \"We Will Rock You\". The video for \"Killer Queen\" had been shot especially for ''Greatest Flix'', as no video had been made for the song on its original release in 1974.<ref name=\"Billboard19811017\" />\n\n'''''Greatest Flix'''''\n#\"Killer Queen\"\n#\"Bohemian Rhapsody\"\n#\"You're My Best Friend\"\n#\"Somebody to Love\"\n#\"Tie Your Mother Down\"\n#\"We Are the Champions\"\n#\"We Will Rock You\"\n#\"We Will Rock You (Live)\"\n#\"Spread Your Wings\"\n#\"Bicycle Race\"\n#\"Fat Bottomed Girls\"\n#\"Don't Stop Me Now\"\n#\"Love of My Life (Live)\"\n#\"Crazy Little Thing Called Love\"\n#\"Save Me\"\n#\"Play the Game\"\n#\"Another One Bites the Dust\"\n#\"Flash\"\n\nNote: On the sleeve notes of the video, \"We Will Rock You\" is incorrectly listed before \"We Are the Champions\".\n\n== Critical reception and legacy ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\" />\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2Score = B+<ref name=\"EW\" />\n| rev3 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/queen/albumguide |title=Queen: Album Guide |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=20 February 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204113916/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/queen/albumguide |archivedate=4 December 2011}}</ref>\n}}\nInitial reviews of the album in the British music press were negative. In ''[[NME]]'' [[Barney Hoskyns]] said, \"All of [their songs], besides 'Another One Bites the Dust', are quite repulsive, unbelievably crass insults to their respective genres and uniformly vulgar music. It was only when Queen took vulgarity to its absolute limit that they stood out.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Barney |last=Hoskyns |authorlink=Barney Hoskyns |title=Queen \u2013 ''Greatest Hits'' |magazine=[[NME]] |page=36 |date=31 October 1981}}</ref> ''[[Melody Maker]]''{{'}}s [[Adam Sweeting]] stated, \"I've never been the slightest bit interested in Queen's ridiculous pomposity and Freddie just makes me snigger, but I suppose songs like 'Killer Queen' are sort of catchy, while anything as preposterous as 'We Will Rock You' deserves an award if only for bad taste\".<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Adam |last=Sweeting |authorlink=Adam Sweeting |title=Queen \u2013 ''Greatest Hits'' |magazine=[[Melody Maker]] |page=18 |date=31 October 1981}}</ref>\n\nHowever, retrospective reviews have rated the album higher: [[Ira Robbins]] gave ''Greatest Hits'' a B+ rating in ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' upon its reissue in 1992,<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,312359,00.html|title=Greatest Hits Review|last=Robbins|first=Ira|authorlink=Ira Robbins|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=13 November 1992|accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref> and William Ruhlmann of [[AllMusic]] awarded the record four and a half stars out of five.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |first=William |last=Ruhlmann |title=''Greatest Hits'' (1981) \u2013 Queen |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/greatest-hits-1981-mw0000939949 |website=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> In an interview in 2003 as part of the [[Arte]] television programme ''Music Planet 2Nite'', [[Radiohead]] guitarist [[Ed O'Brien]] hailed the album as \"impeccable\" and \"absolutely genius\".<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Radiohead live at Le R\u00e9servoir (Paris, France)|series=Music Planet 2nite|network=[[Arte]]|minutes=26:34|date=3 July 2003|quote=Queen did their Greatest Hits, and the first one is impeccable, isn't it? It's absolutely genius.}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nIn the UK, ''Greatest Hits'' debuted at number two on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and climbed to number one the following week, spending four weeks at the top. The album continued to sell well throughout the 1980s, appearing on several UK year-end charts, and by the end of the decade it had become the fourth-biggest selling album in the UK during the 1980s, with sales of over 1.9 million copies.<ref name=\"RM19891216\">{{cite magazine |first=Alan |last=Jones |title=Chartfile |magazine=[[Record Mirror]] |page=45 |date=16 December 1989}}</ref> By 2006, ''Greatest Hits'' had become the [[List of best-selling albums in the United Kingdom|best-selling album in the UK]] and the first album to sell more than five million copies there.<ref>{{cite news |title=Queen head all-time sales chart |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6151050.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=16 November 2006 |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> In February 2014, it was confirmed by the [[Official Charts Company]] that ''Greatest Hits'' had become the first album in the UK to sell over six million copies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen's Greatest Hits becomes first album to sell 6 million in the UK |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/queens-greatest-hits-becomes-first-album-to-sell-6-million-in-the-uk__3758/ |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Queen reach six million album sales in UK |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-26121239 |work=BBC News |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> The same year ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' stated one in three families in the UK owns a copy.<ref>{{cite news |title=Queen's Greatest Hits is first album to sell 6 million UK copies |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/10629578/Queens-Greatest-Hits-is-first-album-to-sell-6-million-UK-copies.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref> As of February 2019 the album has spent a total of 861 weeks on the UK Albums Chart.<ref name=\"UKchart\" />\n\nIn the US the album sold moderately well on initial release in 1981, being certified platinum,<ref name=\"RIAA\" /> and peaked at number 11 on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart on its reissue in 1992.<ref name=\"Billboard200\" /> However, it has since been certified eight times platinum for sales of eight million copies, making it the band's best-selling album there.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |title=Queen's 'Greatest Hits' Becomes First Album to Sell 6 Million in U.K. |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5901176/queen-greatest-hits-becomes-first-album-to-sell-6-million-in-uk |magazine=Billboard |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref> Among the [[Billboard 200#Most weeks on the chart|longest charting albums in the US]], as of April 2020 it has spent 380 weeks on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/queen/chart-history/billboard-200/song/177587|title=Queen Chart History (Billboard 200)|website=Billboard|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> It is also the band's best-selling album worldwide, with total sales of more than 25 million copies.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Pictures: 50 years of pop |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/in_depth/entertainment/2002/jubilee/popup/5.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=17 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |first=Sarah |last=Anderson |title=The 50 best-selling albums ever |url=https://www.nme.com/photos/the-50-best-selling-albums-ever-1419009 |magazine=NME |date=12 November 2010 |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\nThis section includes the track listings for the original ''Greatest Hits'' in its various forms. For other compilations, including the [[Greatest Hits II (Queen album)|second]] and [[Greatest Hits III (Queen album)|third]] ''Greatest Hits'' albums, see the relevant articles.\n\nOn the 17-track UK editions, [[Freddie Mercury]] was the writer of ten of the songs, [[Brian May]] five and [[John Deacon]] two. [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] had not written any songs that had been released as singles for the band at that point.\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 1981 UK edition (EMI) & 2011 UK edition (Island)<br />{{nobold|Has a photograph of the band as its cover.}}\n\n<br />Side one\n| title1          = [[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\n| note1           = from ''[[A Night at the Opera (Queen album)|A Night at the Opera]]'', 1975\n| writer1         = [[Freddie Mercury]]\n| length1         = 5:57\n| title2          = [[Another One Bites the Dust]]\n| note2           = from ''[[The Game (Queen album)|The Game]]'', 1980\n| writer2         = [[John Deacon]]\n| length2         = 3:36\n| title3          = [[Killer Queen]]\n| note3           = from ''[[Sheer Heart Attack]]'', 1974\n| writer3         = Mercury\n| length3         = 2:57\n| title4          = [[Fat Bottomed Girls]]\n| note4           = single version, from ''[[Jazz (Queen album)|Jazz]]'', 1978\n| writer4         = [[Brian May]]\n| length4         = 3:22\n| title5          = [[Bicycle Race]]\n| note5           = from ''Jazz'', 1978\n| writer5         = Mercury\n| length5         = 3:01\n| title6          = [[You're My Best Friend (Queen song)|You're My Best Friend]]\n| note6           = from ''A Night at the Opera'', 1975\n| writer6         = Deacon\n| length6         = 2:52\n| title7          = [[Don't Stop Me Now]]\n| note7           = from ''Jazz'', 1978\n| writer7         = Mercury\n| length7         = 3:29\n| title8          = [[Save Me (Queen song)|Save Me]]\n| note8           = single version, from ''The Game'', 1980\n| writer8         = May\n| length8         = 3:48\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| total_length    = 58:44\n|headline         = Side two\n| title9          = [[Crazy Little Thing Called Love]]\n| note9           = from ''The Game'', 1980\n| writer9         = Mercury\n| length9         = 2:42\n| title10         = [[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\n| note10          = from ''[[A Day at the Races (album)|A Day at the Races]]'', 1976\n| writer10        = Mercury\n| length10        = 4:56\n| title11         = [[Now I'm Here]]\n| note11          = from ''Sheer Heart Attack'', 1974\n| writer11        = May\n| length11        = 4:10\n| title12         = [[Good Old-Fashioned Lover Boy]]\n| note12          = from ''A Day at the Races'', 1976\n| writer12        = Mercury\n| length12        = 2:54\n| title13         = [[Play the Game (song)|Play the Game]]\n| note13          = from ''The Game'', 1980\n| writer13        = Mercury\n| length13        = 3:33\n| title14         = [[Flash (Queen song)|Flash]]\n| note14          = single version, from ''[[Flash Gordon (soundtrack)|Flash Gordon]]'', 1980\n| writer14        = May\n| length14        = 2:48\n| title15         = [[Seven Seas of Rhye]]\n| note15          = from ''[[Queen II]]'', 1974\n| writer15        = Mercury\n| length15        = 2:47\n| title16         = [[We Will Rock You]]\n| note16          = from ''[[News of the World (album)|News of the World]]'', 1977\n| writer16        = May\n| length16        = 2:01\n| title17         = [[We Are the Champions]]\n| note17          = from ''News of the World'',